<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1436,151,830]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,697,722]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species can be readily recognized by its coloration especially the pale ochraceous mesonotum, in all other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[414,545,733,758]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Evacanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[414,545,733,758]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Evacanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the subcontinent, the mesonotum is black. The male genitalia are very similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1918" box="[264,362,769,794]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Evacanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bellus">
<emphasis box="[264,362,769,794]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">E. bellus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but the new species differs in having bulbous base from which the distal part of ventral pygofer process arises and the processes of the dorsolateral lobes of the aedeagus are a little shorter and pigmented.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
